---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="About Asteris Commerce. Australian WordPress + WooCommerce + Cart plugin division"
  description="Asteris Commerce is the plugin-products division of My Cosmic Message Pty Ltd, incorporated 2021. The same Sydney-based company has been running Orion Web Service (full-stack WP and WC development and hosting) since 2021. Three plugins: Asteris for WooCommerce, Asteris for WordPress, Asteris Cart. Built from five years of operator pain across real client stores."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="container">
      <h1>About Asteris Commerce</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        A small team, three plugins, an Australian Pty Ltd that's been running WP and WC dev work since 2021. Here's the actual story: who, why, how it's funded, and what it isn't.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="body">
    <div class="container">

      <h2>Who</h2>
      <p>
        Asteris Commerce is the plugin-products division of My Cosmic Message Pty Ltd, an Australian proprietary limited company (ACN 652 358 159, ABN 30 652 358 159), incorporated in New South Wales in 2021. Sole director: Nick Lord. Based in Sydney, Australia. The same Pty Ltd also operates Orion Web Service, a full-stack WordPress and WooCommerce development and hosting business that's been serving Australian and international clients since 2021.
      </p>
      <p>
        I've spent five years building, maintaining, and hosting WooCommerce stores for clients via Orion Web Service. Asteris exists because every single client stack had the same shape: 15 to 20 paid plugins from 12+ vendors, each with its own admin page, update cadence, support inbox, and conflict surface. The plugin I wished existed didn't, so I built it. Then I realised the same logic applied to the non-WC side of WordPress (security, SEO, backups, email), and again to the checkout and funnel layer (CartFlows, FunnelKit, the upsell stack). Those became the second and third products. Asteris isn't a fresh startup. It's a 5-year-old WP services company productising the patterns we've been seeing every day on real client work.
      </p>

      <h2>Why three plugins, not one</h2>
      <p>
        Most WordPress sites don't run WooCommerce. Most WooCommerce stores have plugin needs that go well beyond what a generic WP plugin covers. And the checkout, funnel, and upsell layer in WC is its own distinct problem domain (CartFlows and FunnelKit territory) that benefits from being a focused product rather than buried inside a mega-plugin. Bundling everything into one would dilute all three and force customers to install code they'll never use.
      </p>
      <p>
        So: Asteris for WordPress covers what any WP site needs (Security and Login and 2FA, SEO and AI, Backups and Migration, SMTP and Email Logs, and more). 11 modules at v1.0. Asteris for WooCommerce covers what a WC store specifically needs (SEO, AI Suite, PDF Invoices, Variation Swatches, Wishlist, Side Cart, Coupons, and 13 more). 20 modules at v1.0. Asteris Cart covers the checkout, funnel, upsell, and cart-recovery layer. 22 modules at v1.0. Replaces CartFlows, FunnelKit, and the related funnel stack at a fraction of the combined cost.
      </p>
      <p>
        Some modules genuinely overlap (SEO and AI, Analytics, Links, AI library, Activity Log and Site Health). Those are built once and vendored into all three plugins, so the same code ships everywhere, no plugin depends on another, and customers never have to install more than the one they actually need.
      </p>

      <h2>Funding model</h2>
      <p>
        No VC. No angels. No outside capital at all. Asteris Commerce is funded by:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Orion Web Service revenue. The sister business has been running profitable WP and WC development and hosting work since 2021. That cash flow funds Asteris R&D and ops, so we don't need to sprint for premature revenue or compromise the Module Quality Protocol to ship faster.</li>
        <li>Launch-locked Founder subscriptions. Customers who subscribe during the launch window keep their launch price for as long as their subscription stays continuously active. Hard cap of 100 paid Founders plus 20 competition winners per product. No lifetime-deal trap.</li>
        <li>Standing subscriptions at regular post-launch pricing for new customers after the Founder 100 closes per product.</li>
        <li>Stripe direct via our own licence server. Payments processed by Stripe. Licences issued and managed by our own infrastructure at pay.asteriscommerce.com. We don't touch credit card data.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Recurring revenue funds support. There is no growth-hacker incentive, no quarterly pressure, no exit narrative. The business succeeds or fails on whether the plugins are good enough to keep customers subscribed.
      </p>

      <h2>How we ship</h2>
      <p>
        Both plugins ship under a documented <strong>Module Quality Protocol</strong>: every module must close its Tier 1 (must-have) + Tier 2 (best-of-breed) gap analysis against the dominant commercial competitor BEFORE the next module starts. Tier 3 features get deferred to later releases; the Tier 1+2 floor is non-negotiable. The point of this rule is to prevent shipping thin modules that look complete but fail in real use — the failure mode that turns "all-in-one" bundles into cluttered support-heavy junk drawers.
      </p>
      <p>
        All three plugins target PHP 8.1+ minimum. All three are HPOS-verified, Block Cart and Block Checkout compatible, regression-tested across six themes per release. WordPress Multisite support is planned for v1.1 across all three products.
      </p>

      <h2>What Asteris Commerce isn't</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Not a VC-funded startup</li>
        <li>Not a marketplace or plugin aggregator. We build all the modules ourselves</li>
        <li>Not affiliated with Automattic, WordPress Foundation, or any other vendor</li>
        <li>Not a SaaS. All three products are plugins you install on your own site, with your own data, on your own host</li>
        <li>Not promising features we haven't built. All roadmaps are public</li>
        <li>Not enterprise. We serve solo store owners, freelancers, and small agencies. If you need a dedicated account manager and 24/7 phone support, this isn't the right vendor for you</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Contact</h2>
      <p>
        <a href="mailto:founder@asteriscommerce.com">founder@asteriscommerce.com</a> goes directly to Nick. For product support, use the support address on the relevant product site.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Legal entity:</strong> My Cosmic Message Pty Ltd, ACN 652 358 159, ABN 30 652 358 159. Registered address: Sydney, NSW, Australia.
      </p>

      <h2>See also</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="https://asterisforwoocommerce.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Asteris for WooCommerce</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://asterisforwordpress.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Asteris for WordPress</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://asteriscart.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Asteris Cart</a></li>
        <li><a href="/roadmap">Cross-product roadmap</a></li>
        <li><a href="/press">Press + media kit</a></li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .hero {
    padding: 80px 0 40px;
  }
  h1 {
    font-size: 64px;
    line-height: 1;
    letter-spacing: -2px;
    margin-bottom: 24px;
  }
  .lead {
    font-size: 22px;
    color: var(--c-muted);
  }
  @media (max-width: 700px) { h1 { font-size: 40px; } }

  .body { padding: 40px 0 80px; }
  .body h2 {
    font-size: 32px;
    margin: 40px 0 16px;
    color: var(--c-black);
  }
  .body p {
    font-size: 24px;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: #333;
    margin-bottom: 20px;
  }
  .body p strong { color: var(--c-black); }
  .body ul {
    margin: 0 0 16px 24px;
    color: #333;
  }
  .body ul li {
    font-size: 24px;
    line-height: 1.55;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
  }
  .body a { color: var(--c-orange); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 3px; }
  .body a:hover { color: var(--c-black); }
</style>
